Neural network regression

Well start with an example of using a neural network for a regression task. The data are taken from a Kaggle competition and are based on a set of 77 breakfast cereals. A description of the data is given in the appendix. The last field in the file (rating) is the outcome variable that we will build the network for. Start by loading the packages well need for today:

Neural network in mlr3

Regression neural networks are provided in mlr3 from the nnet package (regr.nnet).

As the network uses weighted sums of the input features, its important that none of these are on very different scales. The easiest way to avoid this is to scale all variables to approximately the same range. The scaling we use here is a min-max transformation or normalization (i.e.each variable is converted to a 0-1 range). This transformation is given by the following equation.

\[ x_i'=\frac{x_i-min(x)}{max(x)-min(x)} \]

We do this in three steps: - First calculate the maximum then minimum value for each variable using the apply() function. - Then we use these to scale the data - effectively setting the smallest value of each variable to 0, the highest value to 1 - Lastly, we make a new dataset that combines these scaled values with the output (rating)

feature_names <- c("calories", "protein", "fat", "sodium", "fiber")
maxs = apply(mydat[, feature_names], 2, max)
mins = apply(mydat[, feature_names], 2, min)
scaled_features = as.data.frame(scale(mydat[, feature_names], 
                                      center = mins, scale = maxs - mins))
scaled_data <- data.frame(rating = mydat$rating, scaled_features)

Now well go through the usual steps of defining our task, performance metric and resampling strategy first. Note that we use the scaled data to create the task, and that we create an outer resampler using k-fold cross-validation, to allow tuning later.

cereal_task <- TaskRegr$new("cereal", backend = scaled_data,
                            target = "rating")
msr_rmse <- msr("regr.rmse")
rsmp_outer <- rsmp("cv", folds = 5)

Before building the neural network, well test a simple linear model to give us a baseline performance score, and to allow us to judge whether a neural network represents an improvement.

lrn_lm <- lrn("regr.lm")

Now run the cross-validation:

rr_lm <- resample(cereal_task, lrn_lm, rsmp_outer)
## INFO  [13:54:35.981] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.lm' on task 'cereal' (iter 1/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.021] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.lm' on task 'cereal' (iter 2/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.037] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.lm' on task 'cereal' (iter 3/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.049] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.lm' on task 'cereal' (iter 4/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.061] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.lm' on task 'cereal' (iter 5/5)
rr_lm$aggregate(msr_rmse)
## regr.rmse 
##  6.347373

For reference, the range of the outcome (rating) is about 10 to 100.

Now well set up a neural network learner. Note that we can specify here the number of nodes in the hidden layer. Well start with 3 nodes to give us a simple model. Note that we specify this directly in the setup of the learner.

lrn_nn <- lrn("regr.nnet", size = 3)

And again, run the resampler:

rr_nn <- resample(cereal_task, lrn_nn, rsmp_outer)
## INFO  [13:54:36.148] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.nnet' on task 'cereal' (iter 1/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.170] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.nnet' on task 'cereal' (iter 2/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.180] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.nnet' on task 'cereal' (iter 3/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.192] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.nnet' on task 'cereal' (iter 4/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.205] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.nnet' on task 'cereal' (iter 5/5)
rr_nn$aggregate(msr_rmse)
## regr.rmse 
##  9.981332

We get a RMSE value of 9.98 which is slightly worse than the original linear model. Lets see if increasing the number of hidden nodes to 5 and the number of learning iterations will improve this:

lrn_nn <- lrn("regr.nnet", size = 10, maxit = 500)
rr_nn <- resample(cereal_task, lrn_nn, rsmp_outer)
rr_nn$aggregate(msr_rmse)
## INFO  [13:54:36.284] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.nnet' on task 'cereal' (iter 1/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.304] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.nnet' on task 'cereal' (iter 2/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.329] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.nnet' on task 'cereal' (iter 3/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.353] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.nnet' on task 'cereal' (iter 4/5)
## INFO  [13:54:36.378] [mlr3] Applying learner 'regr.nnet' on task 'cereal' (iter 5/5)
## regr.rmse 
##  13.97572

This has made the model too complex, as to RMSE has increased substantially. Lets now tune the model to see if we can choose the optimal value for this parameter. First, lets check the available parameters for regr.nnet:

lrn_nn$param_set
## <ParamSet>
##            id    class lower upper nlevels        default value
##  1:      Hess ParamLgl    NA    NA       2          FALSE      
##  2:   MaxNWts ParamInt     1   Inf     Inf           1000      
##  3:       Wts ParamUty    NA    NA     Inf <NoDefault[3]>      
##  4:    abstol ParamDbl  -Inf   Inf     Inf          1e-04      
##  5:  censored ParamLgl    NA    NA       2          FALSE      
##  6: contrasts ParamUty    NA    NA     Inf                     
##  7:     decay ParamDbl  -Inf   Inf     Inf              0      
##  8:      mask ParamUty    NA    NA     Inf <NoDefault[3]>      
##  9:     maxit ParamInt     1   Inf     Inf            100   500
## 10: na.action ParamUty    NA    NA     Inf <NoDefault[3]>      
## 11:      rang ParamDbl  -Inf   Inf     Inf            0.7      
## 12:    reltol ParamDbl  -Inf   Inf     Inf          1e-08

## 14:      skip ParamLgl    NA    NA       2          FALSE      
## 15:    subset ParamUty    NA    NA     Inf <NoDefault[3]>      
## 16:     trace ParamLgl    NA    NA       2           TRUE FALSE

In addition to the number of neurons (size), well also tune the number of iterations (maxit) and the learning decay rate (decay). Next, load the paradox library, and define the parameter space that we will explore:

library(paradox)
## Warning: package 'paradox' was built under R version 4.1.2
tune_ps = ParamSet$new(list(
  ParamInt$new("size", lower = 1, upper = 10),
  ParamInt$new("maxit", lower = 50, upper = 500),
  ParamDbl$new("decay", lower = 0, upper = 1e-4)
))
tune_ps
## <ParamSet>
##       id    class lower upper nlevels        default value
## 1:  size ParamInt     1 1e+01      10 <NoDefault[3]>      
## 2: maxit ParamInt    50 5e+02     451 <NoDefault[3]>      
## 3: decay ParamDbl     0 1e-04     Inf <NoDefault[3]>

Well use a random search strategy to select values of the parameters to test:

tuner = tnr("random_search")

And well define a stopping condition. Well run this for 20 iterations here (20 parameter values). This is a relatively low number to explore a three dimensional parameter space, in practice you would want to increase this (or use a different search strategy).

evals = trm("evals", n_evals = 20)

Lastly, well set up an inner cross-validation strategy for the tuning process. Well use the same k-fold strategy as above, but with \(k=3\):

rsmp_inner <- rsmp("cv", folds = 3)

With all that in place, lets create an AutoTuner that will bring all of this together.

at_nn = AutoTuner$new(tuner,
                      learner = lrn_nn, 
                      resampling = rsmp_inner,
                      measure = msr_rmse, 
                      search_space = tune_ps,
                      terminator = evals)

And finally(!), run the resample function with this. This will run for a little while as it is building 3 * 5 * 20 models.

rr_nn <- resample(cereal_task, 
                  at_nn,
                  rsmp_outer,
                  store_models = TRUE)

We can extract the results of the tuning process (the inner cross validation) as follows:

extract_inner_tuning_results(rr_nn)[,
                                    list(maxit, decay, size, regr.rmse)]
##    maxit        decay size regr.rmse
## 1:   223 7.958538e-05    9  6.644598
## 2:   233 5.351425e-05    3  6.907214
## 3:   232 6.217342e-05    2  8.207253
## 4:   418 3.536190e-05    2  7.232612
## 5:   217 6.643057e-05    7  7.085872

From these results, it would appear that the first set of parameters gives the best result. However, when we extract the RMSE for the test set as follows, this has the highest test RMSE, suggesting that these parameters overfit the model.

rr_nn$score(msr_rmse)[,
                      list(regr.rmse)]
##    regr.rmse
## 1: 12.485796
## 2:  5.179914
## 3:  7.709178
## 4:  7.500225
## 5:  5.936927

The results of the second outer fold result in the lowest overall test error, and well now go ahead and build a full model with these values.

lrn_nn <- lrn("regr.nnet", 
              size = extract_inner_tuning_results(rr_nn)[2]$size,
              maxit = extract_inner_tuning_results(rr_nn)[2]$maxit,
              decay = extract_inner_tuning_results(rr_nn)[2]$decay)
cereal_nn <- lrn_nn$train(cereal_task)
## # weights:  22

Neural network classification

Next, well build a neural network for a classification task. Well use a new dataset, containing credit rankings for over 4000 people (see appendix for a description of the fields). The goal will be to predict Status, a binary outcome with two levels: good and bad. Well start again by reading the data:

credit_data <- read.csv("../datafiles/credit_data.csv")

As we have several categorical variables, we need to make sure that R recognizes these as factors. The following line of code checks each column in the credit_data data frame, and if it contains character data, it then converts it to a factor. Note this is similar to the approach in the previous lab, where we convert individual variables to factors:

credit_data <- credit_data %>% 
  mutate_if(is.character,as.factor) %>%
  mutate_if(is.integer,as.numeric)

As machine learning algorithms cant use missing data to train, we need to decide what to do with these. For this lab, well just exclude them, which results in the loss of about 400 observations, but in the next lab, well explore methods to impute values and use these.

dim(credit_data)
## [1] 4454   14
credit_data <- credit_data %>%
  na.omit() 
dim(credit_data)
## [1] 4039   14

Now lets first set up a classification task with the credit dataset:

credit_task <- TaskClassif$new("credit", backend = credit_data,
                               target = "Status")

As before, well set up a resampler and performance metric:

rsmp_outer <- rsmp("cv", folds = 5)
msr_auc <- msr('classif.auc')

And finally design our neural network. This will have a single hidden layer with 10 nodes:

lrn_nn <- lrn("classif.nnet", size = 10, decay = 1e-5,
              maxit = 500, trace = FALSE)
rr_nn <- resample(credit_task, lrn_nn, rsmp_outer)
rr_nn$aggregate(msr_auc)
## classif.auc 
##   0.6954638

And lets try with a higher number of nodes and a greater number of iterations:

lrn_nn <- lrn("classif.nnet", size = 25, decay = 1e-5, 
              maxit = 1000, trace = FALSE)
rr_nn <- resample(credit_task, lrn_nn, rsmp_outer)
rr_nn$aggregate(msr_auc)
## classif.auc 
##   0.7366834

Exercise

For the exercise, the goal will be to tune the Credit score neural network from the previous section. Using code from the cereal example, set up a nested cross-validation strategy to tune the following parameters:

  • Size of the hidden layer
  • Maximum number of iterations
  • Decay function

You are free to use any cross-validation method for the inner and outer loops, any relevant performance metric (try a few if you are not sure), the parameter space and the tuning method (e.g.grid vs random).

Your answer should consist of the following

  • A description of how you set up the experiment (e.g.number of folds, tuning method, limits on parameters)
  • The values of the parameters from the tuning, along with the inner cross validation results
  • The outer cross-validation results. Note which results give the best performance on the testing data

You should also provide your full R code.
